    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-12-08T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-12-08T07:00:00-05:00" n="219"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d219">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/8013</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Denmark</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_EMF1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Egan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-12-08T13:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 8, 1917, 1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 9, 5.10 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1681. By the Minister. The Norwegian Minister here, Mr.
                        <persName>Irgens</persName>, … says that no mention of the Åland Islands was
                    made in the conference of the three Kings at Christiania.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d219fn1">For further report on this conference, see despatch from
                        the Minister in Norway, No. 605, Dec. 5, received Dec. 26, <hi rend="italic"
                            >post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1096">p. 1096</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>King <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_HVII1">Haakon</persName> had planned
                    to go to Stockholm to thank King <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_SG1"
                        >Gustav</persName> for having initiated the Malmo meeting; but King
                        <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_SG1">Gustav</persName> thought that
                    as a sign that Sweden had unreservedly accepted the secession of Norway it would
                    be well for him to go to Christiania. He was received by the Norwegian people in
                    the streets with sufficient enthusiasm.</p>
                <p>The <hi rend="italic">communiqué</hi> is a reflex as to what occurred preliminary
                    to the meeting of the Interparliamentary Conference consisting of four members
                    from each of the Scandinavian countries to consider the question as to how
                    Denmark, Norway and Sweden might be more united politically and
                    economically.</p>
                <p>The suggestion that any belligerent power should seize a base in Norway was not
                    considered at either of the meetings. Irgens says that Norway relies on the
                    promise of the powers that its neutrality shall not be broken. The three
                    Scandinavian countries he said emphatically would join in repelling such an
                    aggression.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_EMF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Egan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
